english:
  title: Letter in Response to the Mongol Empire's Yuan Marshal
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit this letter in the spring season.

    I have long held in contemplation Your Excellency's esteemed position, and my heart remains forever drawn to you in deepest sincerity, never wavering for even a moment.

    Previously, the Commander Chi Ui-shim, whom I dispatched to accompany your envoy, has returned bearing your instruction: that when your nation departs for home, you would have us know that we must send emissaries in the third lunar month to gather at the place where our people have dwelt. Following your gracious words, I now send forth Commander Chi Ui-shim once more, accompanied by others, to journey to your realm. Regarding the various matters mentioned in your letters, I shall attend to them and report back accordingly, trusting you will take note of this.

    Furthermore, I have reviewed the letter received from the Duke of Huai'an, which states: "Let your nation select families to be sent to the Station at Kaizhouand settle at the foot of Xuancheng Mountain to cultivate the fields."

    Upon reflection, I am deeply moved and grateful that the Great Nation would divide its lands with us, intending thereby that our people might till the earth and sustain themselves. Yet our land suffers greatly—in every region, our people have lost countless cattle and livestock, and our fields lie fallow and overgrown with rank grasses. We cannot even manage to reclaim what little territory we possess. How then could we possibly send forth multitudes of our people, our oxen and beasts, to cultivate the distant borderlands of your vast realm, a thousand leagues away? Such a task exceeds our strength, and reason forbids us to undertake it by force. I can only humbly beseech your magnanimous understanding of our dire circumstances.
  footnotes:
    - Chi Ui-shim (池義深) appears to have been a diplomatic envoy between Goryeo and the Mongol Yuan court.
    - This letter reflects the political tensions of 13th-century Goryeo, which was under significant Mongol pressure and control.
    - The reference to losses of people and livestock likely reflects the devastating effects of Mongol invasions and ongoing warfare on the Korean peninsula.
